Series creator Tim Cain says that although he does not remember who thought of the Enclave, they were explicitly inspired by ''[[The X Files]]'' (1993), which was running during the creation of ''Fallout 2''. He originally envisioned them as neither good nor bad, with the player ultimately deciding themselves whether they thought the group should continue to exist.


==History==
==Appearances==
Their first appearance in the franchise was in ''Fallout 2'', in which the group is attempting to "purify" the wasteland by introducing a modified form of the Forced Evolutionary Virus (FEV) into the water supply, effectively enacting a genocide against all people with traces of [[radiation exposure]], including human wastelanders as well as [[Ghoul_(Fallout)|ghouls]] and Super Mutants.

This features a small questline with Enclave members as enemies, described in-game as remnants. These enemies are unrelated to ''Fallout: New Vegas''<nowiki/>' Enclave remnants, instead originating from ''Fallout 3'''s Enclave.
⚫

Wizlig carries the solution to [[cold fusion]] into the wasteland, carried in a device implanted in his head. He later dies and his head, containing the device, becomes the [[MacGuffin]] of the story. Further exploration of the Enclave is expected in the upcoming Season 2.

'''Psychiatric disorders of childbirth''' ([[parturition]], labor, delivery), as opposed to those of pregnancy or the postpartum period, are psychiatric complications that develop during or immediately following childbirth. Walton was a [[Works Progress Administration|WPA]] [[Federal Art Project]] artist, for whom she created three 1942 limestone relief pieces, "Indian," "Mine Elevator" and "Campbell's Ledge" for the post office in [[Pittston, Pennsylvania]].<ref>Park, Marlene and Gerald E. Markowitz, Democratic Vistas: Post Offices and Public Art in the New Deal, Temple University Press, Philadelphia 1984 p. 227</ref>
Walton was a [[Works Progress Administration|WPA]] [[Federal Art Project]] artist, for whom she created three 1942 limestone relief pieces, "Indian," "Mine Elevator" and "Campbell's Ledge" for the post office in [[Pittston, Pennsylvania]].<ref>Park, Marlene and Gerald E. Markowitz, Democratic Vistas: Post Offices and Public Art in the New Deal, Temple University Press, Philadelphia 1984 p. 227</ref>

She was chosen to create a large outdoor sculpture called "Young Man with Cow" for the [[1939_New_York_World's_Fair]] outside the Agricultural Pavilion.


== Personal life and family ==
== Personal life and family ==

⚫
Walton's husband, James Putnam (19 Jun 1893 - 3 Feb 1966) whom she married in 1926,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~nywestch/NewRoc1902/i911.htm | title=Marion W. Walton }}</ref> worked for the publishing house, the [[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|MacMillan Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/marion-walton-papers-6984/more|title = More Information | A Finding Aid to the Marion Walton papers, 1915-1976}}</ref> They had one child, Christopher and later were divorced.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~nywestch/NewRoc1902/i770.htm#i168 | title=Arthur James Putnam }}</ref>
Walton was the granddaughter of prominent Philadelphian abolitionists [[Edward Wetherill]] and Anna Thorpe Wetherill. Immediately after [[World War I]], she volunteered with the [[American Committee for Devastated France]] as a driver. <ref> {{Cite web | url=https://www.themorgan.org/sites/default/files/exhibitions/online/a-volunteers-story.pdf}}</ref>

⚫
In 1926, Walton married James Putnam (19 Jun 1893 - 3 Feb 1966), who served as a soldier in the American Ambulance Field Service Fund and as an ambulance driver in France in WWI. Later, Putnam <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~nywestch/NewRoc1902/i911.htm | title=Marion W. Walton }}</ref> worked for the publishing house, the [[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|MacMillan Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/marion-walton-papers-6984/more|title = More Information | A Finding Aid to the Marion Walton papers, 1915-1976}}</ref> They had one child, Christopher and later were divorced.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~nywestch/NewRoc1902/i770.htm#i168 | title=Arthur James Putnam }}</ref>


The late 1920s found Walton's mother Blanche Walton very involved in the New York music scene, at one point housing composer [[Béla Bartók]] during an American tour. Her apartment also hosted the first meeting of the [[American Musicological Society]], a meeting that included [[Joseph Schillinger]], [[Charles Seeger]], and [[Joseph Yasser]]. She was also an early supporter of the American composer Henry Cowell and [[Aaron Copland]]<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qV7nBwAAQBAJ&q=%22Marion+Walton+Putnam%22&pg=PT241 |title = Making Music Modern: New York in the 1920s|isbn = 9780190281625|last1 = Oja|first1 = Carol J.|date = 2000-11-16| publisher=Oxford University Press }}</ref>

She was also an early supporter of the American composer Henry Cowell and [[Aaron Copland]]<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qV7nBwAAQBAJ&q=%22Marion+Walton+Putnam%22&pg=PT241 |title = Making Music Modern: New York in the 1920s|isbn = 9780190281625|last1 = Oja|first1 = Carol J.|date = 2000-11-16| publisher=Oxford University Press }}</ref>
